{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01KJpX8c1hohmRGgnquy7GC9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is a test plan request for a document analysis system with three parallel AI reviewers. I need to analyze each behavior and determine:\n1. The minimum level needed to catch real failures\n2. Justification based on the MOCK-MISS, REAL-INFRA, MOCK-HIDE, LLM-DEP, MULTI-STEP questions\n3. A test description that actually requires that level\n4. Confidence distribution across the 5 levels\n5. Whether the plan is internally consistent\n\nLet me work through each behavior:\n\n**Behavior 1: The clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) present in the contract.**\n\nKey analysis:\n- This is a single AI reviewer performing extraction\n- Correctness depends on what a real LLM produces (it's an extraction task)\n- Different LLM outputs = different key terms identified\n- Even with the same LLM, non-determinism or different runs could produce different results\n- A mock that returns fixed extracted terms would always pass, hiding failures where the real LLM misses a key term\n- LLM-DEP: YES - this is classification/extraction, outcomes depend on the real model\n- MOCK-HIDE: YES - mocking would hide real extraction failures\n- This requires Agentic level - need real LLM to test that extraction is complete\n\n**Behavior 2: The risk assessor flags language that would be problematic under the configured risk policy, even when the problematic phrasing is indirect or euphemistic.**\n\nKey analysis:\n- This is a single AI reviewer performing risk assessment\n- Correctness depends on the real LLM's ability to detect indirect/euphemistic language\n- The \"even when indirect or euphemistic\" part is critical - this tests semantic understanding\n- A mock risk assessor with a fixed set of patterns would miss indirect phrasings\n- LLM-DEP: YES - requires real LLM to assess semantic risk in language\n\n\n- MOCK-HIDE: YES - a mock with pattern matching would hide failures on indirect language\n- This requires Agentic level\n\n**Behavior 3: The compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction.**\n\nKey analysis:\n- This is a single AI reviewer performing compliance checking\n- Correctness depends on the real LLM's knowledge of regulatory requirements\n- Different jurisdictions have different requirements - this is knowledge-heavy\n- A mock that returns fixed compliance status would hide failures on jurisdiction-specific requirements\n- LLM-DEP: YES - requires real LLM with jurisdiction-specific knowledge\n- MOCK-HIDE: YES - mocking would hide real compliance failures\n- This requires Agentic level\n\n**Behavior 4: When two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments, the merge step preserves both assessments with attribution.**\n\nKey analysis:\n- This involves multiple reviewers producing outputs that then get merged\n- The merge logic itself is deterministic - it's orchestration, not LLM-dependent\n- I can mock the individual reviewer outputs and test whether the merge correctly preserves both with attribution\n- MULTI-STEP: YES - involves multiple AI steps feeding into a merge operation\n- MOCK-HIDE: NO - mocking the reviewer outputs doesn't hide failures in the merge logic itself\n- LLM-DEP: NO - the merge step's correctness doesn't depend on real LLM behavior\n- This requires Integration level - need to verify the merge preserves both assessments and their sources correctly The merge function itself is deterministic—it combines extractor and risk assessor outputs while preserving both. Testing this requires wiring the two reviewers' outputs together with conflicting data to verify nothing gets dropped or misattributed. Since the question frames this as \"when two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments,\" I need to test the reviewers plus merge as an integrated unit.\n\nFor the full pipeline, all three reviewers dispatch independently, their results get collected, and then merge into a single report. Using actual contract content means the LLM calls are real, not mocked. The critical verification is that every individual reviewer's findings make it through to the final output without loss.\n\nLM-DEP applies here—all three real language models are required. This is a Workflow-level concern since it involves multiple agentic steps in sequence. Now I'm assessing probability distributions across test levels for each behavior.\n\nThe Clause Extractor needs a real LLM to catch what mock patterns would miss—semantic nuances in how clauses are phrased. Risk Assessor similarly requires actual language understanding to detect indirect risk signals that rule-based mocking can't replicate. Compliance Checker faces the same constraint.\n\nFor Merge Conflict Handling, I can actually test this differently. Real failures here—dropped outputs, lost attribution, unmarked conflicts—are all detectable with fixed mock reviewer inputs. The minimum viable test level is Unit, since the merge logic itself is deterministic and doesn't depend on LLM quality. Unit testing gets 0.40 probability, Integration gets 0.50 since combining reviewers with fixed outputs adds value, and Agentic drops to 0.05 since I don't need a real LLM to validate the merge function itself. outputs as arguments. The description mentions \"when two reviewers flag,\" which implies testing actual reviewer components rather than isolated mocks. Given the document analysis context, I'd expect the reviewers to be real objects that need to work together.\n\nThe realistic minimum is probably Integration level—testing two actual reviewer components alongside the merge logic, or at least verifying how their outputs combine. To catch real failures like dropped outputs, lost attribution, malformed structures, or missing conflict markers, I need to see how the merge function actually handles the combined reviewer data rather than testing it in isolation.\n\nIf merge is a pure function accepting fixed inputs, a Unit test could work. But real systems typically need to receive outputs from actual reviewer objects, parse different formats, and validate both are present—all things that require Integration testing. The test should verify that when one reviewer marks a term as \"standard\" and another flags it as \"high risk,\" both assessments appear in the merged report with clear source attribution.\n\nI'm reconsidering the probabilities though. A genuine failure in merge conflict handling would occur if the code accidentally drops one of the outputs entirely, or if it doesn't properly wire the reviewer components together. That's more likely caught by Integration testing with actual components wired in than by Unit testing with mocks. I'd weight Integration at 0.50, Unit at 0.35, and the others lower since System and Agentic don't add value here.\n\nActually, let me reconsider what a real failure looks like. If the merge function is: `return {\"risk\": risk_result}` and accidentally omits the extractor output, a Unit test with fixed inputs would catch that. But if the failure is in how the three reviewers' results are orchestrated together, that's Workflow-level. For just the merge logic itself, Unit and Integration are both viable, so I'll split them roughly equally at 0.45 each.\n\nFor the full pipeline test that explicitly involves all three reviewers working together, that's clearly Workflow-level since it requires coordinating multiple components across the entire system. involves subprocess/network calls. For a single reviewer, I could test at the Agentic level, but that wouldn't validate the full pipeline orchestration. The Workflow level with multiple sequential agentic steps is where real failures surface—when results get lost during collection or merge operations.\n\nNow I need to reconsider what \"minimum level needed\" actually means. The instructions define it as the lowest testing level that would reliably catch a real failure, not just any level that could work. This shifts my assessment significantly.\n\nFor the Clause Extractor, a Unit test could catch the failure if the extractor misses a key term like a party name or date—I just need to verify the extraction logic directly against the model's output. merges are deterministic functions operating on structured data, then yes—a unit test can verify that when two reviewers assess the same clause differently, both assessments and their sources are retained. For instance, testing merge with inputs like `{\"clause_id\": \"5\", \"assessment\": \"safe\"}` and `{\"clause_id\": \"5\", \"assessment\": \"risky\", \"reviewer\": \"B\"}` should preserve both with clear attribution.\n\nIntegration testing could also catch this, but it's not necessary if the merge logic itself is sound. The minimum is Unit, though I'm less confident here—around 0.70 for Unit versus 0.25 for Integration, since the real complexity might emerge only with actual reviewer outputs.\n\nFor Behavior 5, the full pipeline losing findings is different. Unit testing individual merge operations won't catch this because the failure involves the entire flow—how data moves from multiple reviewers through collection, transformation, and merging stages.\n\nThis is fundamentally a Workflow concern because it spans multiple LLM calls (one per reviewer), their orchestration, result aggregation, and final merge. A real failure here could be parallel dispatch missing a reviewer, collection dropping a result, or merge failing on three outputs. Testing at Integration level with mocked reviewers might catch some issues, but the behavior explicitly describes the sequence of dispatching to all three, collecting, and merging—that's the workflow definition.\n\nConfidence for Behavior 5:\n- Unit: 0.05 - Can't test the full sequence\n- Integration: 0.15 - Partial coverage with mocks\n- System: 0.10 - Subprocess/network issues possible\n- Agentic: 0.15 - Individual calls work, but orchestration matters\n- Workflow: 0.55 - This is the appropriate level for multi-step coordination\n\nThe minimum is Workflow because the behavior requires testing multiple sequential agentic steps, not just individual LLM calls.\n\nFor Behavior 1, the clause extractor's correctness depends on the actual LLM's extraction ability. A mock with fixed outputs would miss real failures where the model fails to identify key terms like parties, dates, obligations, or penalties. The risk assessor must detect problematic language under the configured risk policy, including indirect or euphemistic phrasings that pattern matching alone would miss—like \"circumstances beyond our control\" as a liability disclaimer. This requires semantic understanding that only a real LLM provides. I need to test with actual contracts containing both direct risk language (\"we are not liable\") and indirect variants across multiple risk policies, verifying the LLM flags all instances correctly. The test is Agentic level since it depends on the LLM's classification capability rather than mocked behavior.\n\nFor the compliance checker, jurisdiction-specific regulatory knowledge is embedded in the LLM itself, so testing across GDPR, CCPA, and other regulatory frameworks requires the real model's understanding of nuanced requirements. I'll use real contract examples designed to test compliance for each jurisdiction and verify the checker correctly identifies when contracts meet or fail jurisdiction-specific requirements. This is also Agentic level since hardcoding compliance logic for specific jurisdictions wouldn't catch gaps in the LLM's actual knowledge.\n\nThe merge conflict handling is different—when two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments, the merge step should preserve both with clear attribution. This is deterministic logic that can be tested at the Unit level with fixed, conflicting outputs from the reviewers. The failure mode (dropping one assessment or losing attribution) lives in the merge code itself, which unit testing can catch without needing real LLMs.\n\nFor the full pipeline, I need to test all three reviewers running in parallel, collecting their results, and merging them into a unified report. This requires orchestrating multiple independent agentic steps and handling potential failures like losing a result during collection or merging three outputs together. Testing at lower levels wouldn't catch these orchestration failures across all three reviewers, so this is a true Workflow-level test that needs all three real reviewer components working together.\n\nThe test should submit a real contract and verify that all three reviewers complete, their results are collected without loss, the merged report includes findings from all three with clear attribution, and the pipeline handles diverse contracts consistently. Level Probabilities: Unit=0.00, Integration=0.05, System=0.03, Agentic=0.10, Workflow=0.82\n\nVerifying the probability distributions sum correctly across all five test cases. Structuring the output now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13809,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13809},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bdc782c1-2655-4ad6-a955-285b6fe122fc","uuid":"e4968c13-d767-40be-857f-6599cbcd8734"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01KJpX8c1hohmRGgnquy7GC9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Looking at this document analysis system with parallel AI reviewers, I need to determine what level of test infrastructure can actually catch real failures in each behavior.\n\nLet me work through the key analysis for each:\n\n**Behaviors 1-3 (Individual Reviewers):** Each reviewer is an LLM-based component. The \"real failure\" isn't a logic bug—it's that the LLM gives wrong output (misses a term, misses indirect risk language, gives wrong compliance assessment). Mocking the LLM always returns what we tell it to, hiding the actual failure. These require **Agentic** level.\n\n**Behavior 4 (Merge Conflict Handling):** The merge logic is deterministic code. Given two conflicting outputs, does it preserve both with attribution? This is a pure function test—can provide fixed, disagreeing inputs and verify merge doesn't drop one. No LLM dependency here. **Unit** level is sufficient to catch a real bug (e.g., accidental deletion of one assessment).\n\n**Behavior 5 (Full Pipeline):** This isn't just one reviewer or the merge—it's orchestrating three independent parallel LLM calls, collecting results, and merging. A real failure could be data loss during parallel result collection, or orchestration bugs. Testing one reviewer at a time (Agentic) misses orchestration bugs. This needs **Workflow** level to test the full multi-step agentic pipeline."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13809,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13809},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bdc782c1-2655-4ad6-a955-285b6fe122fc","uuid":"0e661162-500d-46e2-a584-5aa75addddbc"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01KJpX8c1hohmRGgnquy7GC9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_013grB2ZmpwXxaVja6Go3263","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The clause extractor identifies all key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) present in the contract.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends entirely on the real LLM's extraction capability. A mock extractor that returns fixed terms would hide real failures where the LLM misses subtle key terms or misinterprets legal language. Testing this behavior requires actual document input and real LLM inference to verify extraction completeness—you cannot know whether the LLM is finding all terms without running it on real contracts.","test_description":"Test that when a real contract containing specific key terms (party names, dates, payment amounts, obligation descriptions, penalty clauses) is submitted to the extractor, all of them are identified. Use contracts where terms are phrased in typical legal language, including complex obligation descriptions. Verify that the extracted terms match a ground-truth set. If the LLM has temperature > 0, run multiple times to assess consistency, or use temperature=0 for deterministic output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires real LLM extraction on actual documents, which is Agentic-level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.9,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The risk assessor flags language that would be problematic under the configured risk policy, even when the problematic phrasing is indirect or euphemistic.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Detecting indirect or euphemistic risk language requires the semantic understanding of a real LLM. A mock risk assessor using pattern matching or regex would systematically miss indirect phrasings (e.g., 'circumstances beyond our control' as euphemism for liability exclusion). The behavior explicitly tests semantic understanding—only a real LLM can determine whether phrasing is euphemistic under a given risk policy.","test_description":"Test that the risk assessor flags both direct risk language (e.g., 'Company has no liability') and indirect/euphemistic risk language (e.g., 'Buyer assumes responsibility for unforeseen conditions') under the configured risk policy. Use real contract excerpts designed to test the policy's sensitivity to both obvious and subtle risk language. Verify the assessor correctly identifies both types and that the risk flag includes explanation of why the phrasing was flagged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires real LLM semantic classification, which is Agentic-level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.9,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all applicable regulatory requirements for the configured jurisdiction.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Regulatory knowledge is embedded in the LLM itself. The compliance checker must know jurisdiction-specific requirements (GDPR for EU, CCPA for California, etc.) and evaluate contracts against them. A mock that hardcodes compliance rules for specific jurisdictions would not test the LLM's actual knowledge of regulatory nuances and would hide gaps in what the LLM knows. Real jurisdiction-specific regulatory assessment requires the actual LLM.","test_description":"Test the compliance checker against real contract examples for at least two different jurisdictions (e.g., GDPR-governed EU jurisdiction and CCPA-governed California). For each jurisdiction, provide contracts that both satisfy and violate that jurisdiction's key requirements. Verify the checker correctly identifies compliance status and explains which specific requirements are met or violated. Document any jurisdiction-specific failures as part of validating the LLM's regulatory knowledge.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires real LLM reasoning about jurisdiction-specific regulatory requirements, which is Agentic-level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.9,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments (e.g., extractor says 'standard' but risk assessor says 'high risk'), the merge step preserves both assessments with attribution.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The merge logic is deterministic code that combines two outputs. Given fixed reviewer outputs (whether real or mocked), the merge function either correctly preserves both assessments with attribution or it doesn't. A real failure would be the merge code dropping one assessment, losing attribution, or corrupting the output structure. This can all be caught by unit-testing the merge function with fixed conflicting inputs, without needing real LLM calls.","test_description":"Unit test the merge function with fixed, conflicting outputs from the extractor and risk assessor. Example: extractor returns {clause_id: 'clause_5', term_type: 'payment_obligation', assessment: 'standard'} and risk assessor returns {clause_id: 'clause_5', risk_level: 'high'}. Assert that the merged output includes both assessments with clear source attribution (e.g., 'extractor_assessment: standard', 'risk_assessment: high'). Test edge cases: (1) one reviewer returns empty, (2) both return data for the same clause ID, (3) conflicting formats or missing fields. Verify attribution is never lost and no assessment is silently dropped.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test uses fixed mock inputs and tests deterministic merge logic, which is Unit-level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full pipeline — dispatching to all three reviewers, collecting results, merging into a unified report — completes correctly for a real contract without losing any individual reviewer's findings.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This behavior requires orchestrating three independent agentic steps (three parallel LLM calls to extractor, risk assessor, compliance checker) followed by collection and merge. A real failure could occur in the orchestration layer (e.g., parallel dispatch hangs, one result is lost during collection, concurrent writes corrupt the merge). Testing at Agentic level (single reviewer) or Integration level (mocked reviewers) would not catch orchestration failures across all three real reviewers operating in parallel. This is a true multi-step workflow: initiate 3 LLM calls → collect results → merge, which is only testable at Workflow level.","test_description":"Test the full pipeline end-to-end by submitting real contracts to the document analysis system. Verify: (1) all three reviewers are invoked and complete without timeout; (2) results from each reviewer are collected without loss (compare total findings count before/after collection); (3) the unified report includes findings from all three reviewers and each is clearly attributed; (4) the report is well-formed and can be parsed. Run with diverse contracts (different clause types, lengths, complexity) to ensure all three reviewers produce meaningful output. Run the full pipeline multiple times to check for non-determinism or intermittent data loss.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires real calls to three reviewers orchestrated in sequence with result collection, which is Workflow-level.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.82}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13809,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13809},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bdc782c1-2655-4ad6-a955-285b6fe122fc","uuid":"583584dc-af63-462a-8863-adac8a6770be"}
